    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n1987" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">γάρ</span></b>  (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">γέ,
            ἄρα</span>): <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">for, namely;</span> but often not to be
          translated, as in strong asseverations (esp. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἦ
            γάρ</span>), <i><span class="en">Il. 1.293</span></i>, 342, 355,
          and in questions, <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ὦ Κίρκη, πῶς γάρ με κέλεαι σοὶ
            ἤπιον εἶναι</span>, ‘how <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">canst</span> thou bid me?’ <i><span class="en">Od. 10.337</span></i>; similarly after
          interjections, and in wishes, <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">αἲ γάρ,
            εἰ</span> or <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">εἴθε γάρ</span>. The causal
            (<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">for</span>) and explanatory (<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">namely</span>) uses
          need no illustration. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἀλλὰ... γάρ</span>,
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">but yet, but really</span>, <i><span class="en">Il.
            7.242</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Od. 10.202</span></i>; freq. in
          combination (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">γάρ</span>) <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">δή, οὖν, ῥά, τέ, τοί</span>.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
